The document was too long to read directly, so here is a detailed summary of all sections:

The paper titled "Human Capital and Development Accounting: New Evidence from Wage Gains at Migration" by Lutz Hendricks and Todd Schoellman investigates the role of human capital in explaining cross-country income differences. The study uses data on pre- and post-migration wages of U.S. immigrants to estimate the contribution of human capital to development accounting, highlighting that wages increase at migration but by less than half of the GDP per worker gap between countries. This suggests that human capital accounts for a substantial portion of cross-country income disparities.

Key methodologies include analyzing data from the New Immigrant Survey (NIS) and the Migration Projects (Mexican Migration Project and Latin American Migration Project). These datasets provide insights into immigrants' pre- and post-migration wages, allowing the researchers to measure wage gains and differentiate the effects of human capital from physical capital and total factor productivity (TFP).

The study finds that, on average, the wage gain at migration is 38% of the GDP per worker gap, leading to the conclusion that human capital accounts for 62% of income differences. The results indicate that the wage gains vary with education level, with less-educated immigrants experiencing larger gains, consistent with the concept of imperfect substitution between skill types. This supports the finding that the role of human capital in development accounting ranges between one-half and two-thirds, with a point estimate of 60% under additional assumptions.

